Question: Which of the following JavaScript functions correctly replaces a div with a form containing a textarea for editing a user's bio?

A) function editBio(bio) {
     document.getElementById("bio").innerHTML = '
     <form action="profile.editbio.php" method="post">
     <textarea cols="40" rows="10" name="bio" id="bio" maxlength="275">'+ bio +'</textarea><br>
     <input type="submit" value="Update"></form>
     ';
   }

B) function editBio(bio) {
     document.getElementById("bio").innerHTML = '<form action="profile.editbio.php" method="post">'
                                                +'<textarea cols="40" rows="10" name="bio" id="bio" maxlength="275">'+ bio +'</textarea><br>'
                                                +'<input type="submit" value="Update"></form>';
   }

C) function editBio(bio) {
     document.getElementById("bio").innerHTML = `
     <form action="profile.editbio.php" method="post">
     <textarea cols="40" rows="10" name="bio" id="bio" maxlength="275">${bio}</textarea><br>
     <input type="submit" value="Update"></form>
     `;
   }

D) function editBio(bio) {
     document.getElementById("bio").innerHTML = '<form action="profile.editbio.php" method="post">\
     <textarea cols="40" rows="10" name="bio" id="bio" maxlength="275">'+ bio +'</textarea><br>\
     <input type="submit" value="Update"></form>';
   }

Correct Answer: B

Explanation: Option B is correct because it properly concatenates the string across multiple lines, avoiding the "Unexpected end of input" error. Option A fails because it uses multiline strings without proper concatenation. Option C uses template literals, which are valid in modern JavaScript but weren't mentioned in the original context. Option D uses backslashes for line continuation, which is not a recommended practice in JavaScript for multiline strings.

